{
  "id": "0492c2ef-3f74-4b9b-abd4-bffa4294392a",
  "slug": "intrastate-offering-compliance",
  "name": "Intrastate Offering Compliance (Rule 147/147A)",
  "summary": "This skill produces a defensible compliance analysis and execution plan for intrastate securities offerings under Securities Act Rules 147 or 147A where the issuer registers the offering at the state level (commonly by qualification) rather than relying on federal covered-security preemption. It guides the executing LLM through selecting the appropriate safe harbor, substantiating issuer eligibility under principal-place-of-business and doing-business tests, implementing rigorous investor residency verification, controlling advertising and communications, imposing resale restrictions, aligning disclosure with state registration and antifraud standards, and analyzing integration risk. The skill embeds ethical guardrails, mandatory anti-hallucination verification requirements for all legal authorities, and an attorney-review mandate before any output is used.",
  "content": "# Intrastate Offering Compliance (Rule 147 / Rule 147A) \u2014 State-Registered (Non-NSMIA) Offerings\n\n## 1. Opening Context\n\nThis skill guides the execution of a defensible compliance analysis and offering plan for an intrastate securities offering under Securities Act Rules 147 or 147A, where the issuer registers (or qualifies) the offering at the state level rather than relying on federal covered-security preemption under NSMIA. The work product is a structured memorandum and execution plan that a securities lawyer would use to confirm issuer eligibility, structure the offering, draft legends and subscription materials, coordinate state registration by qualification, and reduce the risk of an inadvertent federal Section 5 violation, state enforcement action, rescission exposure, or investor litigation.\n\nIntrastate offerings are deceptively technical. Unlike many other exemptions, a single offer or sale to a non-resident can, in certain circumstances, jeopardize the entire exemption for the offering. When that happens, the issuer may be left without a federal exemption and without a workable \"repair\" strategy, exposing the issuer and its principals to regulatory scrutiny, rescission claims by all investors, and potential disqualification consequences that can impair future financings. High-quality execution requires three things: a fact-grounded determination that Rule 147 or 147A is available, a tightly controlled offering process designed to keep offers and sales within a single state and to evidence investor residency, and a state-law registration package that is internally consistent with federal positioning and aligned with the state administrator's expectations.\n\nScope boundaries: This skill covers structuring and compliance analysis for Rules 147/147A and the related state registration-by-qualification workflow. It does not replace jurisdiction-specific legal advice, does not itself draft a complete state registration filing for any particular state, and does not address broker-dealer registration, investment adviser issues, ERISA plan asset concerns, tax structuring, or ongoing Exchange Act reporting triggers except to flag when specialist review is required. Any final plan must be reviewed and signed off by a licensed attorney in the relevant state.\n\n## 2. Understanding the Context and Purpose\n\nIntrastate offerings exist because Congress and the SEC have historically recognized that purely local capital formation\u2014conducted by a local issuer, for local investors, in a single state\u2014can be regulated primarily at the state level without full federal registration. Section 3(a)(11) of the Securities Act of 1933 (15 U.S.C. \u00a7 77c(a)(11)) provides the statutory intrastate exemption. Rules 147 and 147A (17 C.F.R. \u00a7 230.147 and \u00a7 230.147A) provide safe harbors that clarify when an offering will be treated as intrastate for Securities Act purposes.\n\nStrategically, an issuer chooses the intrastate route when it wishes to raise capital from a local investor base that may include non-accredited individuals, without the \"accredited investor\" restrictions of Rule 506(b) or 506(c), and when it is willing to submit to substantive state securities review. The trade-off is the loss of \"covered security\" status under Section 18 of the Securities Act (NSMIA). This means the issuer cannot avoid state-level regulation; instead, the offering must be registered with the state securities administrator (usually through Registration by Qualification) or find a specific state-level exemption, such as a state crowdfunding statute.\n\nThis workflow typically arises when the issuer's investor base is truly local (community businesses, local real estate or operating companies, local economic development initiatives), the issuer is willing to be reviewed by the state regulator and deliver state-compliant disclosure, and the issuer does not qualify for, does not want to use, or cannot practically use a federal exemption that would preempt substantive state registration. State registration by qualification is often chosen when there is retail participation, advertising is expected, and the issuer wants a more \"public offering-like\" pathway with state regulator sign-off.\n\nThe audience for this skill's output includes the supervising securities attorney, the issuer's management and finance team, sometimes the underwriter or placement agent (if any), and\u2014indirectly\u2014the state securities examiner who will review the registration. In a dispute, the output may be scrutinized by plaintiffs' counsel, a state enforcement attorney, or (if the exemption is challenged) by the SEC. The analysis must therefore be written with adversarial awareness: assume someone later will ask, \"Show me exactly how you ensured every purchaser was in-state, and show me how you satisfied the issuer eligibility requirements.\"\n\n## 3. Prerequisites and Information Gathering\n\nBefore performing substantive analysis, the executing LLM must collect and review enough information to evaluate both sides of the intrastate premise: issuer eligibility (is this truly a local issuer \"doing business\" in the state?) and offering execution (can the issuer actually confine sales to in-state residents and evidence that confinement?). The LLM should request missing items and pause if the user cannot supply them, because intrastate compliance is extremely fact-dependent and the absence of a single fact can flip the conclusion.\n\nFirst, obtain the issuer's organizational and operational footprint: the entity type and jurisdiction of formation; current and historic principal office locations; a narrative of operations describing where business is actually conducted; the addresses of real property used in the business; headcount by state; a list of executive officers and where they work; and the most recent financial statements (audited or unaudited) and general ledger summaries showing where revenues are generated and where assets are located. If the issuer has multiple subsidiaries or affiliated entities, collect an organizational chart and identify which entity will be the offering issuer.\n\nSecond, obtain the proposed offering terms and distribution plan: the security type; target raise amount (minimum and maximum); a specific use-of-proceeds budget; anticipated purchaser profile (retail versus accredited, local community investors, employee investors); whether any selling agents, finders, or platforms will be used; and whether there will be general solicitation and, if so, what channels (internet ads, social media, local newspapers, radio). Collect drafts of any offering materials, including pitch decks, term sheets, offering circulars, subscription agreements, investor questionnaires, escrow agreements, marketing scripts, and website landing pages.\n\nThird, collect the state-law posture: the offering state; the intended state registration path (by qualification, by coordination, or by notification) and the reason the issuer is not relying on a federal covered-security route; any prior state filings by the issuer; any correspondence with the state securities administrator; and any state-specific disclosure requirements, merit review standards, escrow requirements, sales commission limits, investor suitability requirements, and legend requirements. If the issuer has already engaged with the regulator, obtain examiner comments.\n\nFourth, collect \"bad actor\" and disqualification-related facts: identify directors, executive officers, general partners or managing members, 20% beneficial owners, promoters, compensated solicitors, and any placement agents; collect their disciplinary histories. Even if Rules 147/147A do not include the same disqualification provisions as Rule 506(d), state law may contain analogous bars or heightened scrutiny.\n\nFifth, collect offering logistics needed to police residency: the proposed subscription workflow (online versus paper), identity verification practices, how residency will be confirmed, whether the issuer will accept funds from out-of-state banks or addresses, and what steps will be used to prevent secondary trading out of state during the restricted period.\n\nFinally, the LLM should ask: \"Please confirm the state in which the offering will occur and the company's principal place of business address. Has the issuer previously offered these or similar securities to anyone outside of this state in the last six months?\" This last question is critical for integration analysis. The LLM should label assumptions clearly when the user cannot provide a fact.\n\n## 4. Step-by-Step Process\n\n### Step 1: Select the Correct Intrastate Safe Harbor (Rule 147 vs. Rule 147A)\n\nThe first critical decision is determining whether to proceed under Rule 147 (the traditional Section 3(a)(11) safe harbor) or Rule 147A (the modernized exemption adopted by the SEC in October 2016). While they appear similar, their legal foundations differ significantly. Rule 147 is a safe harbor for the Section 3(a)(11) statutory exemption, meaning it is subject to the inherent limitations of that statute, including the requirement that the issuer be incorporated or organized in the state where the offering occurs. Rule 147A was promulgated under the SEC's general exemptive authority (Section 28 of the Securities Act), making it more flexible.\n\nIn most modern contexts, Rule 147A will be the preferred path. Rule 147A allows an issuer to be incorporated in one state (for example, Delaware) but conduct an intrastate offering in another state (for example, Texas), provided its \"principal place of business\" is in the offering state. Furthermore, Rule 147A permits general solicitation and advertising\u2014including on the unrestricted internet\u2014so long as actual sales are made only to residents of the state. In contrast, Rule 147 risks a violation if an out-of-state resident views an \"offer,\" though the SEC has provided some leeway for internet disclaimers.\n\nExecution guidance: (i) determine the offering state (the single state in which all sales will occur); (ii) determine whether the issuer's formation state is the same as the offering state; (iii) determine whether the issuer's principal place of business is in the offering state; and (iv) assess whether internet advertising is central to the distribution plan. If the issuer is incorporated out of state but genuinely operates in the offering state, Rule 147A is the only viable safe harbor.\n\nThe LLM must not rely on memory for the precise text of these rules. It must verify the current rule text by searching the Electronic Code of Federal Regulations (eCFR) at https://www.ecfr.gov for 17 C.F.R. \u00a7 230.147 and \u00a7 230.147A and cite the retrieved text with URLs. The SEC's 2016 adopting release (SEC Release No. 33-10238, \"Exemptions to Facilitate Intrastate and Regional Securities Offerings\") is the primary interpretive source and should be retrieved and cited.\n\nCommon mistake: Choosing Rule 147 for a Delaware corporation doing business in New York. This is a per se violation of Rule 147, which requires the state of incorporation and the state of the offering to be identical. Use Rule 147A instead.\n\nAdversarial awareness: Plaintiffs' counsel and regulators will look for contemporaneous proof that the issuer consciously selected a rule and built procedures around that rule's elements. A post hoc claim that \"we thought everyone was local\" is weak. The work product should document the choice and the reasoning.\n\n### Step 2: Analyze and Document Issuer Eligibility Under the \"Doing Business\" Tests\n\nThe exemption rises or falls first on issuer eligibility. The analysis should be written as if an examiner or enforcement attorney will audit it: identify the rule element, state the facts, and tie the facts to the element.\n\nUnder both Rule 147 and 147A, the issuer must satisfy at least one of the following \"doing business\" tests to demonstrate a substantial in-state connection. The LLM must verify the current quantitative thresholds by retrieving the rule text from eCFR; as of the 2016 rulemaking, the tests require that at least 80% of the relevant metric be in-state, but this must be confirmed against the current rule:\n\n**Revenue Test:** At least 80% of the issuer's consolidated gross revenues must be derived from operations or property within the state.\n\n**Asset Test:** At least 80% of the issuer's consolidated assets must be located within the state.\n\n**Proceeds Test:** At least 80% of the net proceeds from the offering must be intended for use, and actually used, in connection with operations within the state.\n\n**Employee/Operations Test:** A majority of the issuer's employees must be based in the state. (The LLM should verify this specific formulation against the current rule text.)\n\nFor the \"principal place of business\" requirement (which applies to Rule 147A for issuers organized out of state), the analysis must identify the issuer's \"nerve center\"\u2014where officers direct, control, and coordinate the company's activities. Do not accept superficial statements such as \"HQ is in the state.\" Pin down where corporate records are maintained, where day-to-day management occurs, and where key employees work. If the issuer uses a virtual office, remote workforce, or distributed management, the analysis must be more detailed and may require attorney judgment.\n\nThe LLM should create a structured \"issuer eligibility memo\" that (i) computes the relevant percentage metrics from financials and supporting schedules, (ii) identifies the measurement period required by the rule, and (iii) ties each metric to documentary support (financial statements, tax filings, bank statements, leases, payroll records). This memo can later be repurposed into responses to state examiner comments.\n\nPerform a \"stress test\" on the numbers. If a company is a SaaS provider with servers in Virginia but headquarters in Ohio, the revenue test might be difficult to satisfy in Ohio if revenue is deemed derived from the Virginia servers. In such cases, the practitioner should lean on the proceeds test or the principal place of business test. If the issuer is near a threshold, the LLM should flag that the exemption is fragile and propose adjustments (changing the issuer entity, revising use of proceeds, delaying the offering until metrics are satisfied).\n\nIllustrative execution language: \"The issuer satisfies the 'doing business' requirement because (a) approximately [X]% of consolidated assets are located in-state as evidenced by the balance sheet and fixed-asset register dated [date]; (b) approximately [X]% of revenues are generated from in-state customers as shown by the sales-by-ship-to-address analysis for [period]; and (c) the planned use of proceeds is for in-state operational expansion (leasehold improvements at [address], equipment at [address], and hiring in-state employees). This conclusion depends on confirming the rule's quantitative thresholds against the current eCFR text.\"\n\nCommon mistakes include using the parent's in-state activities to qualify a subsidiary issuer without analyzing which entity is the issuer; ignoring consolidated versus standalone financial presentation; and failing to reconcile use-of-proceeds claims with actual planned spending. If a company used 25% of the proceeds to pay off a loan to a bank in a different state, opposing counsel will argue the 80% proceeds test was failed. Every dollar must be tracked.\n\nAdversarial awareness: Opposing counsel will look for inconsistencies\u2014marketing materials suggesting national expansion while the intrastate analysis claims local operations, or proceeds being used to pay out-of-state debts or acquire out-of-state assets. State examiners often focus on whether proceeds truly stay in-state.\n\n### Step 3: Design and Implement Purchaser Residency Verification\n\nOnce issuer eligibility is plausible, the most operationally dangerous requirement is ensuring that every sale is made only to residents of the offering state. Under Rules 147 and 147A, securities may only be sold to persons who are residents of the state at the time of the sale. For individuals, residency is determined by their \"principal residence.\" For business entities, it is determined by the location of their \"principal place of business.\" The LLM must verify these definitions against the current rule text.\n\nThe legal risk is binary: a single non-resident sale can destroy the exemption for that transaction and can cast doubt on the entire offering. The LLM must therefore design a residency verification and recordkeeping protocol that is both practical and defensible, treating residency as a fact to be verified, not a box to be checked.\n\nAt a minimum, the subscription package should include an investor questionnaire with a residency representation and consent to provide supporting documentation; a requirement for documentary proof of residency (state driver's license, voter registration card, state tax return excerpt, or utility bill) with a defined procedure for reviewing and retaining it; and a certification by the issuer (or its counsel or placement agent) that residency was confirmed prior to acceptance of the subscription.\n\nIf subscriptions are taken online, the protocol should address IP geolocation and mailing address mismatches, but the LLM must not overstate what IP proves. IP checks can be a supplemental red-flag tool, not a legal determination of residency. The LLM should propose a workflow: pre-screening (state-only marketing where feasible), gating questions, document upload, compliance review, then acceptance and countersignature.\n\nIllustrative subscription language (to be tailored and attorney-reviewed): \"Subscriber represents and warrants that Subscriber's principal residence is located at [Address] in the State of [State], and that Subscriber has no present intention of moving their principal residence to another state. Subscriber acknowledges that the securities have not been registered under the Securities Act of 1933 and may not be sold or transferred except in compliance with applicable federal and state securities laws, including the intrastate offering restrictions. Subscriber agrees to provide documentation reasonably requested by the Company to confirm residency.\"\n\nEntity investors require special scrutiny. If an entity is formed specifically to acquire the securities, the practitioner must \"look through\" the entity and ensure every beneficial owner is a resident of the state. The LLM must verify how Rules 147 and 147A treat entity residency\u2014the rules may define entity residency by principal place of business\u2014but a look-through analysis is prudent compliance practice even where the rule permits reliance on entity-level residency.\n\nCommon mistakes include accepting entity investors without analyzing their residency; accepting subscriptions funded from out-of-state accounts without follow-up; relying solely on a representation without any diligence; and allowing \"friends and family\" exceptions\u2014there are none.\n\nAdversarial awareness: If the offering later fails, the first discovery request will be \"produce all documents evidencing investor residency and your procedures.\" A coherent file for each investor\u2014with a copy of a driver's license or utility bill\u2014is the difference between a manageable issue and a crisis.\n\nJurisdiction-specific consideration: States may define \"resident\" differently under state securities law for purposes of state registration. Even if federal intrastate rules govern for Securities Act purposes, the state administrator may require additional residency evidence or may apply its own definitions. The practitioner should resolve any conflict in favor of the more restrictive definition.\n\n### Step 4: Control Offers, Advertising, and Communications\n\nIntrastate compliance is not only about who buys; it is also about how offers are made. Modern communications create spillover: websites are accessible everywhere, social media is shared, and email is forwarded. The LLM must build an \"offers and communications\" strategy that aligns with the selected rule.\n\nThe critical distinction: Rule 147A permits general solicitation and general advertising, including through unrestricted internet channels, so long as (a) the actual sales are made only to residents of the state and (b) the issuer includes legends and disclaimers that the offering is limited to state residents. Rule 147, by contrast, risks a violation if an out-of-state person views an \"offer,\" though the SEC has provided some accommodation for passive internet presence with appropriate disclaimers. The LLM must verify these distinctions against the current rule text and SEC guidance.\n\nAs a practical matter, the LLM should recommend layered controls. The issuer should use offering legends on all written materials; include state-only gating on offering webpages (an affirmative representation of state residency before viewing materials); avoid paid advertising targeted beyond the state; and train all personnel not to discuss the offering with out-of-state persons. If the issuer cannot control communications\u2014for example, if it has a national following online\u2014intrastate may be inappropriate.\n\nIllustrative legend language (must be verified against rule and state requirements): \"The securities described herein have not been registered under the Securities Act of 1933 and are being offered and sold only to residents of the State of [State] pursuant to an exemption from registration. This offering is available only to residents of [State]. Any sale or transfer to non-residents of [State] is prohibited during the applicable restricted period and may be unlawful.\"\n\nCommon mistakes include keeping a public \"invest\" page live without gating; running social media campaigns with broad geotargeting; and allowing third parties (influencers, referral sources, platforms) to post offering links that reach out-of-state persons.\n\nAdversarial awareness: Regulators may review public web archives, social media posts, and paid ad targeting parameters. Assume everything is discoverable. The output should instruct the issuer to preserve copies of all advertisements and to document targeting settings.\n\nJurisdiction-specific consideration: Some states require specific legend wording, filing of advertising with the regulator, or pre-clearance of certain promotional materials in registered offerings. The LLM should instruct counsel to confirm the state's advertising filing and pre-approval rules.\n\n### Step 5: Implement Resale Restrictions and Transfer Controls During the Restricted Period\n\nIntrastate offerings impose a restricted period during which resales to out-of-state persons can undermine the intrastate character of the offering. Under Rules 147 and 147A, as adopted in the 2016 rulemaking, the restricted period is six months from the date of the sale by the issuer. During this period, any resale must be made only to persons resident within the same state. The LLM must verify this period against the current rule text via eCFR.\n\nTo enforce this requirement, the issuer should place a restrictive legend on certificates or book-entry statements; issue stop-transfer instructions to the transfer agent (or maintain internal ledger controls if uncertificated); include contractual transfer restrictions in the subscription agreement; and ensure the issuer has a process to evaluate any requested transfers during the restricted period. If the security is intended to be freely transferable or tradeable on a secondary market, the intrastate pathway is generally inconsistent.\n\nIllustrative transfer restriction clause (to be attorney-reviewed): \"For a period of six months from the date of sale, the securities may not be resold or transferred to any person who is not a resident of the State of [State], and any attempted transfer in violation of this restriction shall be void and shall not be recognized by the Company.\"\n\nIllustrative certificate legend: \"THESE SECURITIES HAVE NOT BEEN REGISTERED UNDER THE SECURITIES ACT OF 1933. FOR A PERIOD OF SIX MONTHS FROM THE DATE OF THE SALE BY THE ISSUER OF THESE SECURITIES, ANY RESALE SHALL BE MADE ONLY TO PERSONS RESIDENT WITHIN THE STATE OF [STATE].\"\n\nCommon mistakes include failing to coordinate with a transfer agent; issuing unrestricted electronic securities through systems that allow transfers; and omitting clear procedures for legend placement, removal, and secondary transfers.\n\nAdversarial awareness: If a resale occurs to a non-resident during the restricted period, the question will be whether the issuer took \"reasonable steps\" to prevent it. A well-documented control environment is critical.\n\nJurisdiction-specific consideration: State corporate law and UCC Article 8 mechanics affect how transfer restrictions must be noted and enforced for certificated versus uncertificated securities. Counsel must ensure restrictions are properly \"conspicuously noted\" and enforceable under the issuer's governing law.\n\n### Step 6: Execute State Registration by Qualification\n\nBecause this skill is specifically for offerings that rely on state registration rather than federal preemption, state registration is a primary deliverable, not an afterthought. Registration by Qualification is the state analogue to a full disclosure filing: it commonly requires a detailed offering document, issuer financials, sales materials, consent to service of process, and filing fees. In many states, it also triggers \"merit review\"\u2014an examiner may require changes to the terms (escrow arrangements, commission limits, use of proceeds, dilution) as a condition of effectiveness.\n\nThe LLM should begin by determining which state registration pathway applies. Under the Uniform Securities Act (and state variants, whether based on the 1956, 1985, or 2002 version), the three classic pathways are registration by notification, coordination, and qualification. Intrastate offerings frequently use qualification because there is no federal registration statement to coordinate with. The LLM must confirm the offering state's statutory scheme and current administrative rules via the state regulator's website or official code publication and cite them. The NASAA (North American Securities Administrators Association) website at https://www.nasaa.org provides state-specific links and model rules that are a useful starting point.\n\nIn a merit review, the state regulator evaluates the substantive fairness of the deal. The examiner may object if the founders' \"cheap stock\" is too far below the offering price; if voting rights are deemed inequitable; if commissions paid to finders or placement agents are excessive; or if the escrow arrangements for minimum offering amounts are inadequate. The practitioner must be prepared for a comment-letter process that can be as rigorous as SEC review, and sometimes more so.\n\nDisclosure content must be aligned with both state requirements and general antifraud standards. Even though the offering is registered at the state level, Securities Act Section 17(a) (15 U.S.C. \u00a7 77q(a)) and Exchange Act Rule 10b-5 (17 C.F.R. \u00a7 240.10b-5) antifraud principles apply to statements made in connection with the offer and sale; state blue sky antifraud provisions also apply. The LLM should therefore structure disclosure around: business description and risk factors; use of proceeds; dilution and capitalization; conflicts of interest and related-party transactions; plan of distribution and selling compensation; financial statements (including state-specific audit requirements, which vary\u2014some states require audited financials above certain offering sizes, others accept reviewed or compiled statements); and intrastate-specific risks (loss of exemption consequences, transfer restrictions, liquidity limitations).\n\nIllustrative risk factor language: \"If we fail to comply with intrastate offering requirements, purchasers may have rescission rights and regulators could seek to halt the offering or impose penalties. Determining compliance involves factual and legal considerations, including investor residency and restrictions on resales, and there can be no assurance that regulators or courts will agree with our position.\"\n\nCommon mistakes include treating state registration as a simple form filing; omitting robust risk factors because \"the state will review it\"; and allowing inconsistent numbers between state forms, the offering document, and marketing materials.\n\nAdversarial awareness: State examiners will compare every piece of marketing to the filed disclosure. Plaintiffs will later allege omissions. The LLM's output should instruct the issuer to maintain a single-source-of-truth approach: all communications must match the filed offering document.\n\nJurisdiction-specific examples for orientation (the LLM must verify current rules before relying on these): California has historically imposed strict \"fair, just, and equitable\" merit review standards through its Department of Financial Protection and Innovation (DFPI). Texas has developed specific intrastate crowdfunding rules. New York's Martin Act grants the Attorney General broad enforcement authority, and even federally exempt offerings may face additional state registration obligations. These are illustrative only; the state regulator's current rules and guidance must be confirmed for any specific offering.\n\n### Step 7: Conduct Integration Analysis and Develop Contingency Plans\n\nIntrastate offerings do not occur in a vacuum. The LLM must analyze whether other offerings by the issuer could be \"integrated\" with the intrastate offering in a way that undermines the exemption, and it must propose a sequencing plan. Under the SEC's 2021 harmonization of the integration framework (17 C.F.R. \u00a7 230.152), there is a general principle and several safe harbors. One key safe harbor provides that offerings separated by more than 30 calendar days will generally not be integrated if the issuer can show that each offering stands on its own merits and complies with its own exemption requirements. The LLM must verify the current text of Rule 152 via eCFR.\n\nIn practice, the LLM should ask: Has the issuer recently raised money under Rule 506, Regulation Crowdfunding, Regulation A, or through other private placements? Are there concurrent offerings planned? Are there offers being made to out-of-state investors in another round? If yes, intrastate compliance is high risk unless the offerings are carefully segregated with separate materials, separate investor pools, and documented compliance decisions.\n\nThe output should include contingency planning: what the issuer will do if an out-of-state subscription is received (reject it and document the rejection); what happens if an investor is later found not to be a resident (consult counsel immediately, evaluate rescission offers, consider state and SEC remediation); and whether a backup federal exemption (often Rule 506(b)) could be available if the issuer must pivot. The LLM should caution that \"switching\" exemptions mid-offering is not a free do-over and can create its own integration, disclosure, and general solicitation issues.\n\nCommon mistakes include running a Rule 506(c) internet campaign concurrently with an intrastate offering; or using the same offering materials and subscription link for both offerings.\n\nAdversarial awareness: Integration is a favorite attack line in enforcement and rescission actions. A clean timeline, separate materials, and documented compliance decisions reduce risk.\n\n## 5. Critical Legal Standards and Compliance\n\nThis workflow implicates both substantive securities regulation and core legal ethics. The LLM must treat legal authority as verification-sensitive and avoid hallucinated citations.\n\n### Federal Securities Law\n\nThe primary federal authorities are Securities Act Section 5 (registration requirement, 15 U.S.C. \u00a7 77e); Section 3(a)(11) (intrastate exemption, 15 U.S.C. \u00a7 77c(a)(11)); Rule 147 (17 C.F.R. \u00a7 230.147) and Rule 147A (17 C.F.R. \u00a7 230.147A) (safe harbors); Rule 152 (17 C.F.R. \u00a7 230.152) (integration framework); and the antifraud provisions of Securities Act Section 17(a) (15 U.S.C. \u00a7 77q(a)) and Exchange Act Rule 10b-5 (17 C.F.R. \u00a7 240.10b-5). The LLM must verify and cite the current text of Rules 147, 147A, and 152 from official sources (eCFR at https://www.ecfr.gov and SEC.gov) before quoting thresholds, time periods, or definitions.\n\n### State Securities Law\n\nState law touchpoints include the offering state's securities act (blue sky law), its rules on registration by qualification (forms, financial statement requirements, escrow or impound provisions, suitability standards), broker-dealer and agent registration requirements for anyone compensated to sell securities, and state antifraud provisions. Most states have adopted a version of the Uniform Securities Act (1956 or 2002 revision), but adoption varies significantly. Because these are state-specific and frequently amended, every state-law claim must either be supported by a current citation to the state's official code or regulations, or be flagged for attorney confirmation.\n\n### Professional Responsibility\n\nModel Rule 1.1 (Competence) requires the practitioner to possess requisite knowledge of both federal SEC rules and the specific blue sky laws of the state. Securities law is a specialized field where generalist knowledge is often insufficient. Model Rule 1.3 (Diligence) requires attention to intrastate compliance on an ongoing basis\u2014the exemption fails when teams \"set and forget\" controls.\n\nModel Rule 1.6 (Confidentiality) applies to all issuer financials, cap table data, disciplinary histories, and investor lists. The LLM should instruct users not to paste sensitive personal data unless necessary, and to redact SSNs and nonessential PII.\n\nModel Rule 3.3 (Candor Toward the Tribunal) applies to filings with state securities commissions. Providing false information about issuer residency or financial health is a violation of both securities law and ethical rules. Model Rule 4.1 (Truthfulness in Statements to Others) informs how counsel must present facts in offering materials and investor communications. Model Rule 1.2(d) prohibits a lawyer from counseling or assisting a client in conduct the lawyer knows is criminal or fraudulent; if the lawyer knows the client is selling to out-of-state residents and misrepresenting it, the lawyer must withdraw.\n\nModel Rule 1.7 (Conflicts of Interest) concerns arise if counsel represents the issuer and also investors, or if a local intermediary is a longstanding client. Conflict checks must be performed before giving investor-facing advice.\n\n### Malpractice Risk Areas\n\nThe primary malpractice risk areas include misstating rule thresholds or time periods; failing to detect that the issuer cannot satisfy the doing-business test; allowing uncontrolled internet offers; failing to handle entity investor residency correctly; ignoring broker-dealer registration triggers for compensated finders; and creating inconsistent disclosures between state filings and marketing. If the practitioner is asked to provide a legal opinion that the offering is exempt, the opinion must be heavily qualified by the factual assumptions regarding residency and the doing-business tests. Mitigation across all areas requires verified legal research, written compliance procedures, and contemporaneous documentation.\n\n## 6. Quality Control and Review\n\nQuality control for an intrastate state-registered offering is best approached as an \"audit simulation\": assume a regulator or plaintiff will review the file and ask for proof.\n\nThe \"Math\" Audit requires re-calculating the 80% tests based on the most recent financials. Does the issuer still qualify? If the issuer has recently opened an out-of-state office or made an out-of-state acquisition, does it affect the eligibility analysis? Every dollar of proceeds must be tracked against the use-of-proceeds schedule.\n\nThe Factual Support Audit requires confirming that every eligibility conclusion is tied to specific documents with dates. If the memo claims a specified percentage of revenues are in-state, it must cite a revenue schedule with a date range and methodology. Unsupported assertions are a common failure mode.\n\nThe Internal Consistency Audit requires confirming that offering terms, use of proceeds, fees and commissions, and risk disclosures match across the state registration forms, the offering document, the subscription agreement, and all marketing materials. The team should maintain a controlled set of numbers (cap table, valuation, offering expenses) and a change log.\n\nThe Legend and Publicity Audit requires reviewing all stock certificates or electronic book-entry statements for the required restrictive legend; reviewing the company's website and social media for state-residency disclaimers (mandatory under Rule 147A); and confirming that no marketing has been directed at out-of-state persons without appropriate gating.\n\nThe Investor File Audit requires confirming that there is documentary evidence of residency (driver's license, utility bill, or equivalent) in the file for every subscriber. Do not close the offering until the file is complete.\n\nOperational Implementability requires confirming that the controls described in the compliance plan are realistic for the issuer. If the issuer cannot practically verify residency or control advertising, the correct answer may be to recommend a different exemption strategy.\n\nFinally, this skill must be applied with the understanding that all outputs require attorney review before use and do not constitute legal advice. The LLM must explicitly flag uncertainties, missing facts, and any place where legal research was not independently verified. All citations to rules, statutes, and SEC releases must be confirmed against official sources; any citation the LLM cannot verify via search should be flagged as \"[CITE CHECK REQUIRED \u2014 verify against eCFR or SEC.gov before reliance].\"\n\n## 7. Jurisdiction-Specific Adaptations\n\nThis skill is designed to be used across U.S. jurisdictions, but intrastate offerings are uniquely sensitive to state-by-state differences because the offering is intentionally regulated primarily by the state administrator.\n\nAt the federal level, Rules 147 and 147A are uniform, but their application depends on facts (principal place of business, doing-business metrics, residency verification, and resale restrictions). The LLM should always retrieve and cite the current rule text from eCFR at https://www.ecfr.gov and relevant SEC guidance from SEC.gov. If the issuer is organized in one state and offering in another, the LLM should evaluate Rule 147A, but only after verifying the issuer-eligibility provisions and documenting principal place of business.\n\nAt the state level, adaptation is mandatory. Some states are \"merit review\" jurisdictions that may require escrow of proceeds until minimum offering amounts are met, impose limits on selling expenses, or require certain disclosures. Other states follow a closer-to-\"disclosure-only\" model. Financial statement requirements vary: some states require audited financials above certain offering sizes; others accept reviewed or compiled statements. Legend and advertising filing requirements also vary.\n\nThe LLM should adapt by identifying the offering state's statutory registration pathways and selecting the one that matches the transaction; retrieving the current state securities rules and administrative forms directly from the state regulator's website or official code publication and citing them; and tailoring the state registration plan (timing, examiner interaction, advertising pre-filing, escrow arrangements) to that state's practice. Where the state's materials are not readily accessible, the LLM should flag the issue and instruct attorney confirmation.\n\nThe LLM must also account for issuer-specific multi-state footprints. If the issuer has significant out-of-state operations, customers, or assets, the doing-business test may be difficult to satisfy, and the intrastate pathway may be inappropriate. The output should be candid: the right adaptation may be to recommend abandoning Rule 147/147A in favor of a federal exemption with state notice filings.\n\nAlways check the state-specific definition of \"resident.\" While the SEC defines residency for federal Rule 147/147A purposes, a state may have a different definition for its own registration purposes. Any conflict should be resolved in favor of the more restrictive definition to ensure compliance under both frameworks.",
